# ~/.config/git/ignore — global gitignore for all repositories
#
# This file is read automatically by git (XDG default, no config needed).
# Rules here apply to every repo on this machine.
#
# ─── overriding these rules per project ──────────────────────────────────────
#
# Option 1 — re-include in the project's .gitignore (committed, shared):
#     Add `!<pattern>` to .gitignore, e.g. `!.env` to track a local .env
#     Note: if a parent directory is ignored globally, negate the parent first,
#     then negate the file — bare file negation inside an ignored dir won't work.
#
# Option 2 — re-include in the project's .git/info/exclude (local, not committed):
#     Same `!<pattern>` syntax, affects only your local checkout of that repo.
#     Useful when you don't want to touch the shared .gitignore.
#
# Option 3 — force-stage a specific file once:
#     `git add -f <file>` stages a file regardless of ignore rules.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

